The surface chemical composition of Bi5O7I and CQDs/Bi5O7I samples was explored by XPS (Fig. 4
                     ). Fig. 4a showed the survey spectra of Bi5O7I and 0.5 wt% CQDs/Bi5O7I materials, which contains Bi, O, I and C. Fig. 4b was the high-resolution Bi 4f XPS spectra of Bi5O7I and 0.5 wt% CQDs/Bi5O7I samples. For pure Bi5O7I sample, the binding energies of Bi 4f5/2 and Bi 4f7/2 were 164.3 and 158.8 eV, respectively, which corresponding to Bi3+ in crystal structure [43]. The peak located at 529.6 eV in O 1s was identified as oxygen in the Bi5O7I crystal lattice (Fig. 4c) [44]. As shown in Fig. 4d, the peaks centered at 630.5 and 619.1 eV were attributed to I 3d3/2 and I 3d5/2 
                     [45], respectively. It can been clearly seen that compared to Bi5O7I material, the peaks of Bi 4f and I 3d in the CQDs/Bi5O7I sample showed a slight transfer to lower binding energy, respectively, which indicated the interaction existed between CQDs and Bi5O7I. In high-resolution C 1s spectra (Fig. 4e), peak located at 284.6 eV in Bi5O7I and 0.5 wt% CQDs/Bi5O7I was attributed to extraneous carbon sources, and other two resolved peaks of 0.5 wt% CQDs/Bi5O7I located at 286 and 288.1 eV in Fig. 4f were corresponded to COC bond and CO bond [31], respectively. The XPS analysis was consistent with the XRD and FT-IR analysis.
